WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:05.005
Sleep apnea is one of the most common and
often overlooked respiratory disorders you'll

2
00:00:05.005 --> 00:00:06.644
encounter as a respiratory therapist.

3
00:00:07.304 --> 00:00:09.265
In this lesson, we're going to break it
down in

4
00:00:09.265 --> 00:00:12.425
a way that helps you think clinically, not
just memorize

5
00:00:12.425 --> 00:00:12.944
facts.

6
00:00:13.045 --> 00:00:16.444
At its core, sleep apnea is a disorder of
breathing

7
00:00:16.444 --> 00:00:20.864
during sleep, where airflow is either
reduced or completely stops.

8
00:00:21.385 --> 00:00:23.584
The most common type, obstructive sleep
apnea,

9
00:00:24.264 --> 00:00:27.424
happens when the upper airway collapses
repeatedly during sleep.

10
00:00:27.424 --> 00:00:29.725
Central sleep apnea, on the other hand,

11
00:00:30.125 --> 00:00:33.044
is a failure of the brain to send the
signal to breathe.

12
00:00:33.185 --> 00:00:34.924
So what does that mean for your patient?

13
00:00:35.625 --> 00:00:39.825
Repeated apneic events lead to
intermittent hypoxemia, hypercapnia,

14
00:00:40.104 --> 00:00:41.625
and frequent arousals from sleep.

15
00:00:42.104 --> 00:00:44.805
Over time, this contributes to daytime
fatigue,

16
00:00:45.325 --> 00:00:48.485
cardiovascular strain, pulmonary
hypertension, and even

17
00:00:48.485 --> 00:00:48.904
heart failure.

18
00:00:49.264 --> 00:00:52.965
From an RT perspective, your job is to
recognize the

19
00:00:52.965 --> 00:00:53.284
pattern.

20
00:00:54.145 --> 00:00:56.985
Patients may present with loud snoring,
witnessed apneas,

21
00:00:57.345 --> 00:01:00.465
morning headaches, excessive daytime
sleepiness, or

22
00:01:00.465 --> 00:01:01.525
unexplained hypertension.

23
00:01:02.165 --> 00:01:04.764
But remember, some patients won't look
obvious,

24
00:01:05.124 --> 00:01:06.925
so you need to connect the dots.

25
00:01:07.745 --> 00:01:12.404
Diagnostics are centered around
polysonography and the apnea-hypopnea index,

26
00:01:12.504 --> 00:01:13.485
or AHI.

27
00:01:14.084 --> 00:01:17.605
This tells you how severe the condition is
and guides treatment decisions.

28
00:01:18.525 --> 00:01:20.904
Management is where you play a critical
role.

29
00:01:21.605 --> 00:01:24.824
CPAP is the gold standard for obstructive
sleep apnea, and

30
00:01:24.824 --> 00:01:26.305
patient compliance is everything.

31
00:01:26.904 --> 00:01:29.605
You'll be responsible for mask fitting,
pressure titration,

32
00:01:30.084 --> 00:01:31.805
troubleshooting, and patient education.

33
00:01:31.964 --> 00:01:36.084
In some cases, BiPAP or adaptive
servoventilation may be used,

34
00:01:36.224 --> 00:01:38.864
especially in more complex or central
cases.

35
00:01:39.485 --> 00:01:40.705
Here's your board prep takeaway.

36
00:01:41.444 --> 00:01:43.605
Think obstruction versus control.

37
00:01:44.485 --> 00:01:47.605
Obstructive sleep apnea is a mechanical
airway problem.

38
00:01:48.364 --> 00:01:51.324
Central sleep apnea is a neurological
control problem.

39
00:01:51.605 --> 00:01:55.824
And both can lead to serious long-term
complications if untreated.

40
00:01:56.625 --> 00:01:59.864
As you move through this lesson, focus on
connecting pathophysiology

41
00:01:59.864 --> 00:02:03.205
to clinical presentation, diagnostics, and
intervention.

42
00:02:03.605 --> 00:02:06.425
That's how you'll think like an RT, and
that's how

43
00:02:06.425 --> 00:02:07.464
you'll pass your boards.

